Nepal (Rautahat district, Province Two). 30 Sep 2016. (submitted) A 30-year-old female tested positive for chikungunya virus (IgM) at Sukraraj Tropical and Infectious Disease Hospital on 27 Sep 2016. She was discharged uneventfully 3 days after treatment. According to patient's relative (personnel communication on 30 Sep 2016), she now developed generalized itching. Although she was a resident of Meghauli, Chitwan district, she developed these symptoms while
living in Chandranigahapur-1, Rautahat district (no travel history out of Chandranigahapur at this time), suggesting that chikungunya may have been circulating in this area (personal communication with patient's relative on 30 Sep 2016), but not in Meghauli, Chitwan as Epidemiology and Disease Control Division (EDCD) believes. Thus a careful travel history must be taken to identify potential new cases in area of an index case. To the best of my knowledge, this is the 1st reported case of chikungunya virus infection in Rautahat district of Nepal. Chikungunya virus infection was first reported in 2013 in Nepal [1].

Reference
---------
1. Pun SB, Bastola A, Shah RJ: First report of Chikungunya virus infection in Nepal. J Infect Dev Ctries. 2014 Jun 11; 8(6): 790-2
(Report submitted by Dr Sher Bahadur Pun, MD, PhD, Clinical Research Unit, Sukraraj Tropical and Infectious Disease Hospital, Kathmandu, Nepal)

[ProMED thanks Dr Sher Bahadur Pun, MD, PhD and Dr Anup Bastola, Consultant Tropical Medicine Physician, MD, MCTM of the Sukraraj Tropical and Infectious Disease Hospital who also sent this report.

Maps of Nepal can be seen at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nepalese_Federal_States and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4667167,32849. - Mod. TY]

